<taxonomicName LSID="http://species-id.net/wiki/Platyphora_selva" authority="Daccordi, 1994" authorityName="Daccordi" authorityYear="1994" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora selva" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="selva">Platyphora selva Daccordi, 1994</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="77" pageId="5" pageNumber="76" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="76">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="76">
Within New World 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="5" pageNumber="76" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Chrysomelinae">Chrysomelinae</taxonomicName>
, reports of subsociality until recently were limited to a single species studied at the La Selva Field station in the Atlantic lowlands of Costa Rica (
<bibRefCitation author="Choe, JC" journalOrPublisher="Psyche" pageId="14" pageNumber="85" pagination="63 - 68" title="Maternal care in Labidomera suturella Chevrolat (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae: Chrysomelinae) from Costa Rica." url="10.1155/1989/62318" volume="96" year="1989">Choe 1989</bibRefCitation>
). However a misidentification of that species (not by the author) lead to erroneous attribution of subsocial behavior to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Labidomera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Labidomera suturalis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="suturalis">Labidomera suturalis</taxonomicName>
, rather than to an unidentified species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Platyphora</taxonomicName>
. The species was subsequently described and named 
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora selva" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="selva">Platyphora selva</taxonomicName>
by Daccordi without comments on 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Choe’s">Choe's</normalizedToken>
behavioral observations (
<bibRefCitation author="Daccordi, M" journalOrPublisher="Memorie della Societa Entomologica Italiana" pageId="15" pageNumber="86" pagination="221 - 232" title="Nuove specie di Platyphora della regione neotropicale (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae, Chrysomelinae)." volume="72" year="1993">Daccordi 1993</bibRefCitation>
). As noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Reid, CAM" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="16" pageNumber="87" pagination="373 - 398" title="The morphology and biology of Pterodunga mirabile Daccordi, an unusual subsocial Chrysomeline (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae)." url="10.1080/00222930802586016" volume="43" year="2009">Reid et al. (2009)</bibRefCitation>
, this first record of subsocial behavior in Neotropical chrysomelines led to a number of reports citing the original paper and repeating the taxonomic error (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Windsor, DM" editor="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="Annual Review of Entomology" pageId="17" pageNumber="88" title="Kluwer Academic Publishers, Dordrecht, The Netherlands" url="10.1007/978-94-011-1781-4_4" year="1994">Windsor and Choe 1994</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation pageId="5" pageNumber="76">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Kudô">Kudo</normalizedToken>
and Hasegawa 2003
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Costa, JT" journalOrPublisher="Belknap Press of Harvard University Press, Cambridge, MA" pageId="15" pageNumber="86" title="The other insect societies." year="2006">Costa 2006</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="77" pageId="5" pageNumber="76">
<bibRefCitation author="Choe, JC" journalOrPublisher="Psyche" pageId="14" pageNumber="85" pagination="63 - 68" title="Maternal care in Labidomera suturella Chevrolat (Coleoptera: Chrysomelidae: Chrysomelinae) from Costa Rica." url="10.1155/1989/62318" volume="96" year="1989">Choe (1989)</bibRefCitation>
observed 18 guarding 
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora selva" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="selva">
<pageBreakToken pageId="6" pageNumber="77" start="start">Platyphora</pageBreakToken>
selva
</taxonomicName>
females in two different years, all feeding on 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Lycianthes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lycianthes (Witheringia) heteroclita" order="Solanales" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="heteroclita" subGenus="Witheringia">Lycianthes (Witheringia) heteroclita</taxonomicName>
Sendtm. (
<taxonomicName genus="Solanaceae" lsidName="Solanaceae" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" rank="genus">Solanaceae</taxonomicName>
) in the Atlantic lowlands of Costa Rica. His observations were remarkable in first describing how females of this species tightly guarded offspring by straddling. By removing mothers from roughly half of the families, he was able to demonstrate that guarding was highly effective in preventing predation by the gigantic ponerine ant, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Paraponera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Paraponera clavata" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="clavata">Paraponera clavata</taxonomicName>
Fab. The importance of maternal defenses in reducing losses to parasitoids, however, was not investigated. Further, it was noted that mothers always guarded groups of four or fewer larvae; but eggs of the beetle were never observed during the study. From observations of related taxa (see below) we now suspect that 
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora selva" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="selva">Platyphora selva</taxonomicName>
is not oviparous, but instead deposits temporally isolated clutches of four larvae. This inference remains to be documented and is based on the habits of the morphologically similar species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora microspina" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="microspina">Platyphora microspina</taxonomicName>
, which occurs widely (but rarely) in neighboring Panama. Regrettably, sequence data are not yet available for 
<taxonomicName authority="Gistel, 1857" authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1857" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Platyphora" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platyphora selva" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="selva">Platyphora selva</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
